1. Introduction & Context


Purpose of the Guidance

Target Audience:
- Large hospitals and healthcare providers
- Specialist clinics
- General Practitioners (GPs)
- Small healthcare entities with limited resources
- All health entities equally vulnerable to cyber-attacks
Document Objective:
This ENISA guidance provides practical steps to:
1. Safeguard sensitive data
2. Minimize exposure to common cyber threats
3. Strengthen overall cyber resilience

Healthcare Digital Transformation

Current State:
- Increasing reliance on digital solutions across Europe
- Electronic Health Records (EHR) widespread adoption
- Telemedicine expansion
- Connected medical devices proliferation
- AI-powered diagnostics integration
Associated Risks:
- Ransomware attacks: Service disruption, patient safety impact
- Phishing campaigns: Credential theft, initial access
- System vulnerabilities: Exploitation leading to breaches
- Critical service disruption: Patient care impact
- Patient safety compromise: Direct harm potential
- Trust undermining: Reputation and compliance issues

Risk Mitigation Philosophy

Core Principle:
Many cyber risks can be mitigated through relatively straightforward measures.
Key Protective Measures:
1. Regular system updates
2. Secure backup management
3. Multi-factor authentication (MFA)
Impact:
These basic measures can prevent the vast majority of common cyberattacks.
---

2. Protect Your Systems & Medical Devices


2.1 Know Your ICT Assets

Objective: Complete visibility and inventory of all technology assets
Required Actions:
1. Asset Discovery
	- Scan and monitor all connected systems
	- Identify all medical devices
	- Document network-connected equipment
	- Map interdependencies
	- Maintain up-to-date inventory
2. Legacy System Management
	- Label legacy systems clearly
	- Document limitations and constraints
	- Ringfence legacy systems from main network
	- Create mitigation plans for unsupported systems
	- Plan replacement timelines
3. Asset Categorization
	- Clinical vs. administrative systems
	- Critical vs. non-critical devices
	- Internet-facing vs. internal systems
	- Vendor-managed vs. self-managed
	- Real-time vs. batch processing systems
Best Practices:
- Use automated discovery tools
- Conduct quarterly asset audits
- Tag assets with ownership and criticality
- Document all changes to asset inventory
- Include shadow IT in discovery efforts

2.2 Secure System Configurations

Objective: Reduce attack surface through proper configuration
1. Password Management
Change Default Passwords:
- All medical devices
- Network equipment
- Administrative interfaces
- Application accounts
- Service accounts
Password Requirements:
- Minimum 12 characters
- Complexity requirements (uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols)
- No reuse of previous passwords
- Regular rotation schedules
- Password manager deployment for staff
2. Service and Port Management
Disable Unnecessary Ports:
- Close unused network ports
- Document required open ports
- Regular port scanning audits
- Firewall rule reviews
Disable Unnecessary Services:
- Remove unused protocols (e.g., Telnet, FTP)
- Disable guest accounts
- Remove sample/test accounts
- Turn off unused network services
- Disable legacy protocols
3. Software Management
Uninstall Unnecessary Software:
- Remove unused applications
- Eliminate trial software
- Clear development tools from production
- Remove outdated versions
- Clean up temporary installations
4. Configuration Standards
- Use hardening guides (CIS Benchmarks, vendor recommendations)
- Document baseline configurations
- Apply configurations consistently
- Automate configuration management where possible
- Regular configuration compliance checks

2.3 Access Control

Objective: Ensure only authorized personnel access systems with appropriate permissions
1. Privilege Management
Administrative Privileges:
- Manage administrative account distribution
- Monitor privileged access usage
- Log all administrative actions
- Review privilege assignments quarterly
- Separate admin accounts from regular accounts
Least Privilege Principle:
- Grant minimum necessary permissions
- Role-based access control (RBAC) implementation
- Time-limited elevated privileges
- Just-in-time access provisioning
- Regular access reviews and recertification
2. Password Policies
Strong Password Requirements:
- Minimum length: 12 characters
- Complexity requirements enforced
- No dictionary words
- Account lockout after failed attempts
- Password expiration (90-180 days)
Password Manager Provision:
- Enterprise password manager deployment
- User training on password manager use
- Secure password sharing mechanisms
- Emergency access procedures
- Encrypted password storage
3. Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
MFA Requirements:
- Mandatory for:
	- All online accessible systems
	- Remote access (VPN)
	- Administrative accounts
	- Email systems
	- Cloud applications
	- Patient record systems
MFA Methods:
- Authenticator apps (preferred)
- Hardware tokens
- SMS (least preferred, better than nothing)
- Biometric authentication
- Push notifications
Implementation Priorities:
1. Internet-facing systems (immediate)
2. Administrative access (immediate)
3. Email and collaboration tools (high priority)
4. Internal clinical systems (medium priority)
5. All user accounts (long-term goal)
Access Control Matrix Example:
User Role
System Access
MFA Required
Privilege Level
Review Frequency
