7 years
Yes
6. Recovery Time and Point Objectives
Define RTO/RPO:
- Recovery Time Objective (RTO): Maximum acceptable downtime
	- Critical systems: 4 hours
	- Standard systems: 24 hours
	- Non-critical systems: 72 hours
- Recovery Point Objective (RPO): Maximum acceptable data loss
	- Patient records: 1 hour
	- Administrative data: 24 hours
	- Archival data: 1 week
---

3. Protect Your Networks


3.1 Harden Your Networks

Objective: Create secure, monitored, and segmented network infrastructure
1. Secure Network Protocols
Use Secure Protocols:
- HTTPS instead of HTTP
- SFTP instead of FTP
- SSH instead of Telnet
- SNMPv3 instead of SNMPv1/v2
- Secure LDAP (LDAPS)
- IPSec for VPNs
- TLS 1.2+ for all encrypted connections
Disable Insecure Protocols:
- Telnet
- FTP
- HTTP (for sensitive data)
- SMBv1
- SSLv3, TLS 1.0/1.1
- Clear-text authentication protocols
2. Network Segmentation
Segmentation Strategy:
Core Segments:
1. Clinical Network
	- Patient care systems
	- Medical devices
	- EHR systems
	- Laboratory systems
2. Administrative Network
	- HR systems
	- Finance systems
	- Email and office productivity
	- Management systems
3. Guest Network
	- Public Wi-Fi
	- Patient/visitor access
	- Completely isolated from clinical LAN
4. Medical Device Network
	- Imaging equipment (MRI, CT, X-ray)
	- Patient monitoring systems
	- Laboratory analyzers
	- Infusion pumps
	- Separate VLAN, restricted access
5. IoT/Building Management
	- HVAC controls
	- Physical security systems
	- Environmental monitoring
	- Separate from clinical networks
6. Management Network
	- Network equipment management
	- Server management interfaces
	- Backup systems
	- Jump hosts for administration
Segmentation Benefits:
- Limits lateral movement
- Contains breaches
- Simplifies monitoring
- Meets regulatory requirements
- Reduces PCI DSS scope
Implementation:
- VLANs for logical separation
- Firewalls between segments
- Access control lists (ACLs)
- Zero-trust architecture principles
- Micro-segmentation for critical assets
3. Network Monitoring
24/7 Flow Monitoring & Alerting:
What to Monitor:
- Network traffic volumes
- Protocol usage
- Geographical connections
- Failed connection attempts
- Bandwidth utilization
- Unusual traffic patterns
- Port scanning activities
- Data exfiltration indicators
Alerting Criteria:
- Traffic to known malicious IPs
- Large outbound data transfers
- Connections to unusual countries
- Off-hours administrative access
- Protocol violations
- Threshold breaches
- New device connections
- Suspicious DNS queries
Monitoring Tools:
- Network Traffic Analysis (NTA)
- Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS)
- Intrusion Prevention Systems (IPS)
- Security Information and Event Management (SIEM)
- NetFlow/sFlow analysis
- Packet capture for forensics
Response Procedures:
- Automated containment for critical alerts
- Escalation procedures
- Investigation workflows
- Documentation requirements
- Post-incident reviews

3.2 Corporate Email Protection

Objective: Prevent phishing, malware, and email-based attacks
1. Spam and Phishing Filtering
Enable Hosted Spam/Phish Filtering:
- Cloud-based email security gateway
- Machine learning-based detection
- Reputation scoring
- Sender authentication checking
- Bulk email detection
- Real-time threat intelligence
Filtering Capabilities:
- Spam detection (>99% accuracy goal)
- Phishing detection
- Spear-phishing protection
- Business Email Compromise (BEC) detection
- Impersonation protection
- Brand logo detection
2. Attachment and Link Scanning
Turn On Attachment & Link Scanning:
Sandboxing:
- Detonate attachments in isolated environment
- Analyze behavior before delivery
- Block malicious files
- Quarantine suspicious attachments
- Safe file rewriting (content disarm)
Safe Links:
- URL rewriting for click-time protection
- Real-time reputation checking
- Time-of-click analysis
- Block access to malicious sites
- User warnings for suspicious links
- Link tracking and logging
File Type Controls:
- Block executable attachments (.exe, .scr, .bat)
- Restrict macro-enabled documents
- Control archive files (.zip, .rar)
- Allow only necessary file types
- Auto-decrypt and scan encrypted attachments
3. Domain Spoofing Protection
Enforce Secure Protocols:
SPF (Sender Policy Framework):
- Define authorized sending servers
- Publish SPF records in DNS
- Configure receiving servers to check SPF
- Fail/softfail/neutral policies
DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail):
- Cryptographically sign outbound messages
- Verify signatures on inbound messages
- Rotate signing keys regularly
- Multiple selectors for different mail flows
DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication):
- Build on SPF and DKIM
- Define policy for failed authentication
- Receive reports on email usage
- Progress through p=none → p=quarantine → p=reject
- Monitor reports for legitimate failures
Implementation Steps:
1. Audit current email flows
2. Publish SPF record (start with ~all)
3. Implement DKIM signing
4. Deploy DMARC in monitor mode (p=none)
5. Review reports and fix issues
6. Move to quarantine (p=quarantine)
7. Eventually enforce rejection (p=reject)
Anti-Spoofing Benefits:
- Prevents domain impersonation
- Reduces phishing success
- Improves email deliverability
- Provides visibility into email usage
- Protects brand reputation

3.3 Fortify Internet Access

Objective: Protect Internet-facing assets and control web access
1. Firewall Protection
Deploy Next-Generation Firewalls (NGFW):
Capabilities:
- Traditional packet filtering
- Application awareness and control
- Intrusion prevention (IPS)
- SSL/TLS inspection
- Malware blocking
- URL filtering
- User/group-based policies
- VPN concentrator
- Threat intelligence integration
Firewall Placement:
- Perimeter (Internet boundary)
- Between network segments
- Before/after DMZ
- Protecting data centers
- Branch office connections
Configuration Best Practices:
- Default deny policy
- Explicit allow rules
- Regular rule reviews (quarterly)
- Remove unused rules
- Document all rules with business justification
- Geo-blocking for unnecessary countries
- Rate limiting for connections
2. Web Application Filtering
Apply Web Application Filters:
Web Filtering Categories to Block:
- Malicious sites
- Phishing sites
- Malware distribution
- Command and control servers
- Newly registered domains (high risk)
- Uncategorized sites
- Adult content
- Gambling
- Social media (where appropriate)
- File sharing
- Personal email (where appropriate)
SSL/TLS Inspection:
- Decrypt and inspect encrypted web traffic
- Certificate trust management
- Exemptions for privacy (banking, health portals)
- Performance considerations
- User awareness and consent
3. Internet-Facing System Protection
Shield Your Internet-Facing Systems:
Web Application Firewall (WAF):
- Protect web applications from attacks
- OWASP Top 10 protection
- SQL injection prevention
- Cross-site scripting (XSS) blocking
- Bot management
- API protection
- Virtual patching for vulnerabilities
- Custom rule creation
DDoS Mitigation Service:
- Volumetric attack protection
- Application-layer attack mitigation
- Always-on protection
- Automatic scaling
- Traffic scrubbing centers
- Real-time analytics
- Incident response support
Protected Assets:
- Public websites
- Patient portals
- Telemedicine platforms
- Email servers
- VPN gateways
- API endpoints
- Mobile app backends
Defense-in-Depth Strategy:
```
Internet
    ↓
DDoS Mitigation
    ↓
WAF
    ↓
Next-Gen Firewall
    ↓
IPS
    ↓
Application

```

3.4 Secure Wi-Fi

Objective: Provide secure wireless access for staff and guests while protecting clinical networks
1. Enforce VPN and MFA When Off-Site
Remote Access Security:
VPN Requirements:
- All remote access through VPN only
- No direct Internet exposure of internal systems
- Split-tunneling disabled for corporate access
- Always-on VPN for remote workers
- Per-app VPN for mobile devices
MFA for VPN:
- Mandatory multi-factor authentication
- Certificate-based authentication preferred
- Time-based one-time passwords (TOTP)
- Push notification approval
- Biometric authentication for mobile
- Device compliance checking
Remote Access Policy:
- Approved devices only
- Endpoint security requirements
- Patch level verification
- Personal device restrictions (BYOD policy)
- Session time limits
- Logging and monitoring
2. Wireless Encryption
Use Latest Wireless Encryption Standards:
WPA3 Implementation:
- WPA3-Enterprise for corporate networks
- 192-bit security mode for high-security areas
- Protected Management Frames (PMF)
- Opportunistic Wireless Encryption (OWE) for guest
Fallback Support:
- WPA2 for legacy device compatibility
- Regular assessment of legacy devices
- Migration plan to WPA3-only
- Disable WEP and WPA completely
Certificate-Based Authentication:
- 802.1X with certificates (preferred)
- RADIUS server integration
- Automatic device provisioning
- Certificate lifecycle management
3. Guest Wi-Fi Isolation
Isolate Guest Wi-Fi from Clinical LAN:
Complete Separation:
- Separate SSID for guest network
- Different VLAN
- Separate Internet gateway
- No access to internal resources
- Captive portal for terms of service
- Time-limited access (e.g., 24 hours)
Guest Network Controls:
- Bandwidth limitations
- Content filtering
- User registration (optional)
- Terms acceptance logging
- Device fingerprinting
- Anomaly detection
4. SSID Management
Hide SSIDs for Sensitive Internal Networks:
SSID Strategy:
- Visible SSIDs:
	- Guest network
	- General staff network
- Hidden SSIDs:
	- Clinical devices network
	- Medical equipment network
	- Administrative network
	- Management network
Note: SSID hiding provides obscurity, not security. Still use strong authentication.
5. Wi-Fi Password Management
Create Strong Wi-Fi Passwords:
Password Requirements:
- Minimum 20 characters for WPA2/WPA3
- Mix of character types
- No dictionary words
- Changed quarterly
- Different passwords per SSID
- Secure distribution to authorized users
- Document password changes
Enterprise Authentication:
- Use 802.1X instead of shared passwords where possible
- Individual user credentials
- Automatic credential provisioning
- Integration with Active Directory/LDAP
6. Wi-Fi Security Monitoring
Continuous Wireless Monitoring:
- Rogue access point detection
- Unauthorized client detection
- Interference monitoring
- Coverage gap identification
- Performance metrics
- Client connection auditing
- Intrusion detection on wireless
7. Wi-Fi Network Design Best Practices
Network Type
SSID Visibility
Authentication
Encryption
