4. Mind the Security of Smartphones & E-Care


4.1 Mind the Security of Patient-Operated Devices

Objective: Ensure patient-facing devices and applications are secure by design
1. Fail-Safe Design
Design Controls for Safety:
- Ensure no lasting harm occurs when device is: 
	- Lost
	- Stolen
	- Misused
	- Tampered with
	- Malfunctioning
Safety Principles:
- Graceful degradation
- Fail-safe defaults
- Data minimization on device
- Local data encryption
- Automatic session termination
- Tamper evidence
- Emergency override procedures
Examples of Patient Devices:
- Blood glucose monitors with connectivity
- Remote patient monitoring devices
- Patient portal kiosks
- Medication management apps
- Wearable health trackers
- Home dialysis machines
- Insulin pumps with wireless
- Cardiac monitoring devices
2. Authentication for Patient Devices
Use Strong Individual Credentials:
Requirements:
- Unique credentials per patient
- No shared accounts
- Strong password/PIN requirements
- Biometric authentication where appropriate
- Multi-factor authentication for sensitive functions
- Account lockout after failed attempts
Patient-Friendly Security:
- Balance security with usability
- Clear instructions for patients
- Password reset procedures
- Family member access controls (with consent)
- Emergency access procedures
3. Session Management
Enforce Auto-Logout and Browser/App Data Wipe:
Inactivity Timeout:
- Auto-logout after inactivity
- Recommended: 5-15 minutes for patient portals
- Shorter timeouts for public kiosks (2-3 minutes)
- Longer timeouts for remote monitoring (configurable)
- Warning before auto-logout
Data Clearing:
- Wipe browser/app data on logout
- Clear cache and cookies
- Remove downloaded files
- Close all application windows
- Secure deletion of temporary files
4. Security Recommendations
Provide Clear Security Recommendations:
Patient Education Materials:
- How to create strong passwords
- Recognizing phishing attempts
- Safe device usage
- When to contact support
- How to report suspicious activity
- Privacy settings configuration
Distribution Channels:
- Patient portal messages
- Email communications
- Printed materials at registration
- Video tutorials
- Mobile app onboarding
- Provider verbal instructions
Topics to Cover:
- Password security
- Public Wi-Fi risks
- Physical device security
- Sharing credentials (don't)
- Software update importance
- Recognizing legitimate communications
- Reporting lost/stolen devices

4.2 Enable Secure Mobile Use

Objective: Secure mobile devices used by healthcare staff
1. Application Control
Allow Installation of Approved Apps Only:
Mobile Device Management (MDM):
- Enforce approved app catalog
- Block unapproved app installation
- Containerization for work apps
- Separate personal/work data
- App distribution management
- Automatic app updates
- App configuration policies
Approved App Criteria:
- Vendor reputation and security
- Privacy policy review
- Security testing completed
- HIPAA compliance (or equivalent)
- Regular security updates
- No excessive permissions
- Data encryption at rest and in transit
App Categories:
- Clinical communication (secure messaging)
- EHR access
- Medical references
- Prescribing applications
- Patient monitoring
- Telemedicine
- Medical imaging viewers
2. Remote Device Management
Enable Remote-Wipe if Device is Lost:
Remote Management Capabilities:
- Remote wipe (factory reset)
- Selective wipe (corporate data only)
- Remote lock
- Location tracking
- Alarm activation
- Message display on lock screen
- SIM card management
Procedures:
- Immediate reporting of lost/stolen devices
- IT help desk available 24/7
- Decision authority for remote wipe
- Documentation of wipe actions
- Device replacement process
- Data restoration procedures
3. Device Security Policies
Enforce Strong Passwords and Encryption:
Password Requirements:
- Minimum 6-digit PIN (better: 8+ alphanumeric)
- Biometric authentication (fingerprint, face recognition)
- No simple patterns (1234, repeating digits)
- Failed attempt lockout
- Regular password changes (90 days)
Encryption Requirements:
- Full device encryption mandatory
- Encrypt sensitive data in apps
- Secure boot enabled
- Encrypted communications
- VPN for all data access
- Encrypted backups
4. Device Lockout
Apply 30-Second Automatic Device Lockout:
Auto-Lock Settings:
- Maximum 30 seconds of inactivity
- Shorter for high-security areas (10-15 seconds)
- Immediate lock on closing device
- Lock screen shows no sensitive data
- Swipe/unlock gesture required
Lock Screen Security:
- No notification content displayed
- No control center access when locked
- No Siri/Assistant when locked
- Limited access to camera (no photo review)
- Emergency call only function
5. Mobile Device Security Architecture
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│      Mobile Device (iOS/Android)     │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Device Level                        │
│  • Full disk encryption              │
