5. Keep Patient Records Safe


5.1 Classify & Safeguard

Objective: Protect patient data based on sensitivity through proper classification and encryption
1. Data Identification
Identify Sensitive Data:
Categories of Health Data:
- Highly Sensitive:
	- Mental health records
	- HIV/AIDS status
	- Genetic information
	- Substance abuse treatment
	- Sexual health
	- Reproductive health
- Sensitive:
	- Diagnosis and treatment records
	- Prescription information
	- Lab results
	- Imaging studies
	- Billing information
- Confidential:
	- Patient demographics
	- Insurance information
	- Contact information
	- Appointment schedules
- Public:
	- General health education materials
	- Public hospital information
	- Non-patient specific data
2. Data Tagging
*Tag Data Base on Sensitivity Levels:*
Tagging Implementation:
- Metadata labels on files and databases
- Visual labels on printed materials
- Email classification headers
- Document watermarks
- Access control based on tags
- Automated classification where possible
Classification Scheme Example:
- Red (Highly Sensitive): Restricted access, maximum security
- Orange (Sensitive): Limited access, standard security
- Yellow (Confidential): Internal use, basic security
- Green (Public): No restrictions
Benefits:
- Enables appropriate controls
- Simplifies compliance
- Guides user handling
- Automates data loss prevention
- Facilitates auditing
3. Data Encryption
Encrypt Data at Rest and in Transit:
Encryption at Rest:
- Full disk encryption on all devices
- Database encryption (TDE - Transparent Data Encryption)
- File-level encryption for highly sensitive data
- Backup encryption
- Archive encryption
- USB/portable media encryption
Encryption Standards:
- AES-256 for data at rest
- RSA-2048 or higher for key exchange
- TLS 1.2+ for data in transit
- Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) where appropriate
Encryption in Transit:
- TLS 1.2+ for all web traffic
- VPN for remote access
- SFTP for file transfers
- Encrypted email (S/MIME or PGP)
- Encrypted messaging apps
- Secure API communications
Key Management:
- Centralized key management system
- Hardware Security Modules (HSM) for key storage
- Key rotation policies
- Key backup and recovery procedures
- Separation of duties for key management
- Audit logging of key access
4. Metadata Cleaning
Implement Metadata Cleaning Processes:
Metadata Risks:
- Author information
- Edit history
- GPS coordinates from photos
- Device information
- Software versions
- Network paths
- Comments and track changes
Cleaning Procedures:
- Automated metadata removal tools
- Manual review for sensitive documents
- Standardized document preparation
- Staff training on metadata risks
- Testing of cleaned documents
When to Clean Metadata:
- Before external sharing
- Before public posting
- For legal/court documents
- When sharing with patients
- Research data publication
- Freedom of information requests

5.2 Log and Monitor

Objective: Detect unauthorized access and unusual activity through comprehensive logging
1. Access Logging
Log and Monitor All Access to Health Records:
What to Log:
- User ID accessing records
- Date and time of access
- Patient record accessed
- Type of access (read, write, update, delete)
- Source IP address
- Application used
- Duration of access
- Data exported or printed
Logging Requirements:
- Real-time or near-real-time logging
- Tamper-proof log storage
- Centralized log management
- Long retention (7 years minimum for compliance)
- Protected from unauthorized access
- Regular integrity checks
2. System Monitoring
Check Systems for Unauthorized Access or Data Leaks:
Monitoring Activities:
- User Behavior Analytics (UBA):
	- Baseline normal behavior
	- Detect anomalies
	- Flag suspicious access patterns
	- Identify potential insider threats
- Data Loss Prevention (DLP):
	- Monitor data movement
	- Block unauthorized transfers
	- Scan emails for patient data
	- Control USB/portable media
	- Cloud storage monitoring
- Database Activity Monitoring:
	- Track all database queries
	- Identify unusual queries
	- Block SQL injection attempts
	- Alert on mass data access
Monitoring Tools:
- SIEM (Security Information and Event Management)
- User Entity and Behavior Analytics (UEBA)
- DLP solutions
- Database Activity Monitoring (DAM)
- File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)
- Network Traffic Analysis
3. Alerting
Alert on Unusual Activity:
Alert Triggers:
- High-Risk Activities:
	- Access outside business hours
	- Access from unusual locations
	- Bulk data access or downloads
	- Access to VIP patient records
	- Failed access attempts
	- Privilege escalation
	- Configuration changes
	- Disabled security controls
- Behavioral Anomalies:
	- Significant deviation from baseline
	- Accessing unrelated patient records
	- Print/export spikes
	- Multiple simultaneous logins
	- Unusual search patterns
	- Access after termination
Alert Response:
- Severity classification (critical, high, medium, low)
- Automated containment for critical alerts
- Escalation procedures
- Investigation workflows
- Response time targets
- Documentation requirements
4. Privacy Monitoring
Specific Privacy Controls:
- Break-the-Glass Monitoring:
	- Emergency access without normal authorization
	- Requires justification
	- Review within 24 hours
	- Automatic management notification
- VIP Patient Protection:
	- Enhanced monitoring for celebrity/executive patients
	- Strict need-to-know enforcement
	- Immediate alerts on any access
	- Automatic audit review
- Employee Access to Own Records:
	- Flag and review
	- Separate approval required
	- Enhanced audit trail
5. Audit Requirements
Regular Audit Activities:
Audit Types:
- Access Audits:
	- Monthly random sampling
	- Quarterly comprehensive reviews
	- Targeted investigations
	- Post-incident forensics
- Compliance Audits:
	- Annual privacy audit
	- Regulatory compliance checks
	- Policy adherence review
	- Third-party audits
Audit Metrics:
- Number of access violations
- Time to detect unauthorized access
- Time to respond to alerts
- False positive rates
- User training compliance
- Policy exceptions granted

5.3 Protect Devices & Data

Objective: Prevent physical and environmental threats to data security
1. Physical Device Security
Never Leave Devices Unattended:
Staff Requirements:
- Lock screen when stepping away
- Secure devices when leaving area
- No devices in personal vehicles overnight
- Secure storage when not in use
- Cable locks for workstations
- Laptop security tethers
High-Risk Locations:
- Cafeterias and break rooms
- Conference rooms
- Public areas
- Patient rooms
- Unlocked offices
- Vehicles
2. Clean Desk / Clear Screen Policy
Enforce Clean-Desk/Clear-Screen Policy:
Clean Desk Requirements:
- No patient information left visible
- Lock away files at end of day
- Shred sensitive documents
- Secure portable media
- Lock drawers and cabinets
- Clear whiteboards with patient data
Clear Screen Requirements:
- Lock screen when away (even briefly)
- Position monitors away from public view
- Privacy filters on screens
- No sensitive data on wallpapers
- Auto-lock after 30 seconds inactivity
- Close applications when not in use
3. Secure Printing
Secure Printing of Data:
Secure Print Features:
- Pull-printing (authentication at printer)
- Encrypted print jobs
- Automatic deletion of unclaimed jobs
- Audit trail of all printing
- Watermarks with user ID and timestamp
- Print quotas and restrictions
Printing Procedures:
- Retrieve prints immediately
- Don't print sensitive data unnecessarily
- Use designated secure printers for patient data
- Shred unclaimed prints
- Lock paper trays on shared printers
- Regular clearing of printer memory
4. Asset Lifecycle Security
Secure Asset Lifecycle (Disposal or Reuse):
Decommissioning Process:
For Reuse:
- Complete data wiping (DOD 5220.22-M or better)
- Verification of data removal
- Reinstall clean OS
- Document sanitization
- Repurpose or donate
For Disposal:
- Data destruction certification
- Physical destruction for high-security devices
- Degaussing for magnetic media
- Shredding for hard drives
- Certificate of destruction
- Chain of custody documentation
Asset Disposition Methods:
Device Type
Method
Standard
Verification
Hard Drives (reuse)
7-pass wipe
DOD 5220.22-M
Verification scan
Hard Drives (disposal)
Physical shredding
NIST SP 800-88
Certificate
SSDs
Crypto erase + destruction
NIST SP 800-88
Certificate
Mobile Devices
Factory reset + wipe
Vendor standard
MDM confirmation
Optical Media
Physical destruction
Shredding
Visual inspection
Paper Records
Cross-cut shredding
DIN 66399 P-4
Certificate
5. Cloud and Hosted Services
Verify Vendor SLAs for Cloud EHR & Hosted Apps:
SLA Requirements:
- Uptime guarantees (99.9%+ typical)
- Data backup frequency and retention
- Disaster recovery capabilities
- Security incident notification
- Compliance certifications
- Data residency guarantees
- Right to audit
- Exit strategy and data portability
Security Considerations:
- Data encryption (at rest and in transit)
- Access controls and authentication
- Audit logging
- Patch management
- Vulnerability management
- Incident response procedures
- Business continuity plans
- Insurance coverage
Vendor Assessment:
- SOC 2 Type II report
- ISO 27001 certification
- HITRUST certification
- Compliance attestations (HIPAA, GDPR)
- Penetration test results
- Security questionnaire completion
- Reference checks
- Financial stability
6. Emergency Access
Ensure Patient Data Access in an Emergency:
Emergency Access Planning:
- Offline access to critical systems
- Paper backup procedures
- Downtime protocols
- Alternative communication methods
- Emergency power systems
- Redundant systems and failover
- Geographic distribution of data
Break-Glass Procedures:
- Emergency access accounts
- Clear activation criteria
- Management approval process
- Time-limited access
- Comprehensive logging
- Post-emergency review
- Credential rotation after use
Disaster Scenarios:
- Power outage
- Natural disaster
- Cyber attack (ransomware)
- System failure
- Network outage
- Vendor outage (cloud services)
---

6. Take Incidents Seriously


6.1 Be Prepared

Objective: Establish comprehensive incident response capabilities
1. Incident Response Process
Establish an Incident Response Process:
IR Process Phases:
1. Preparation
	- Develop incident response plan
	- Create playbooks for common scenarios
	- Establish communication channels
	- Procure necessary tools
	- Regular training and drills
2. Detection & Analysis
	- Monitor for security events
	- Analyze alerts and logs
	- Determine incident scope
	- Classify severity
	- Document findings
3. Containment
	- Short-term containment (isolate affected systems)
	- Long-term containment (temporary fixes)
	- Evidence preservation
	- Backup verification
	- System snapshots
4. Eradication
	- Remove malware
	- Delete unauthorized accounts
	- Fix vulnerabilities
	- Strengthen controls
	- Verify clean systems
5. Recovery
	- Restore from clean backups
	- Rebuild compromised systems
	- Verify functionality
	- Monitor for reinfection
	- Gradual return to operations
6. Post-Incident Review
	- Lessons learned meeting
	- Update procedures
	- Improve defenses
	- Staff training updates
	- Executive briefing
2. Team and Responsibilities
Create a Team and Assign Roles:
Incident Response Team Structure:
Core Team Members:
Role
Responsibilities
Authority
Incident Commander
Overall coordination, decision-making, executive communication
Full authority during incident
IT Lead
Technical response, system containment, forensics
System access, vendor contact
Security Lead
Security analysis, threat assessment, evidence handling
Investigation authority
Communications Lead
Internal/external comms, media relations, patient notification
Communication approval
Legal Counsel
Legal compliance, regulatory notification, documentation
Legal guidance
Privacy Officer
Privacy impact assessment, patient notification, GDPR compliance
Privacy decisions
Clinical Lead
Patient safety, clinical operations continuity, workarounds
Clinical operations
Finance Lead
Budget authorization, insurance claims, business impact
Financial authority
Extended Team:
- HR representative (for insider threats)
- Facilities manager (for physical security)
- Third-party vendors
- External forensics consultant
- Law enforcement liaison (if criminal activity)
- Public relations consultant
3. Contact Information
Know and Communicate Who to Contact:
Emergency Contact List:
Internal Contacts:
- IT Help Desk: [24/7 number]
- Security Operations Center: [24/7 number]
- Incident Commander: [mobile]
- CIO/CISO: [mobile]
- CEO: [mobile]
- Legal Counsel: [mobile]
- Privacy Officer: [mobile]
External Contacts:
- National CSIRT: [contact details]
- Supervisory authority: [contact details]
- Law enforcement (cyber crime unit): [contact details]
- Cyber insurance provider: [policy # and contact]
- Forensics firm: [24/7 emergency contact]
- PR firm: [emergency contact]
- Key vendors: 
	- EHR vendor: [support contact]
	- Network provider: [escalation contact]
	- Security tool vendors: [support contacts]
Communication Protocols:
- Primary contact method (phone, secure messaging)
- Escalation procedures
- After-hours contacts
- Chain of command
- Notification thresholds
- Documentation requirements
4. Worst-Case Scenario Planning
Plan for the Worst-Case Scenario:
Catastrophic Scenarios:
Ransomware Outbreak:
- All systems encrypted
- Backups compromised
- Extended downtime
- Patient care impact
- Data exfiltration
- Public disclosure
Response Considerations:
- Paper-based operations
- Patient transfer protocols
- Emergency mode operations
- Media management
- Regulatory notifications (72 hours for GDPR)
- Ransom payment decision process
- Recovery timeline (weeks/months)
Insider Threat:
- Privileged user data theft
- Sabotage of systems
- Patient safety risk
- Ongoing access
- Evidence preservation
Response Considerations:
- Immediate access revocation
- Law enforcement involvement
- Legal proceedings
- HR coordination
- Evidence chain of custody
- Damage assessment
Supply Chain Compromise:
- Vendor system breach
- Malicious software update
- Third-party data breach
- Widespread impact
Response Considerations:
- Vendor communication
- Affected system identification
- Coordinated response
- Media inquiries
- Patient notification
- Contract review
Natural Disaster + Cyber Incident:
- Simultaneous physical and cyber emergency
- Limited staff availability
- Infrastructure damage
- Backup site activation
Response Considerations:
- Priority: Life safety
- Alternative operations site
- Communication challenges
- Resource constraints
- Extended recovery

6.2 Operational Collaboration

Objective: Build strong partnerships for effective incident response
1. Vulnerability Assessment
Perform Vulnerability Scans and Penetration Tests:
Vulnerability Scanning:
- Frequency:
	- Weekly automated scans
	- After significant changes
	- Before go-live of new systems
	- Post-incident verification
- Scope:
	- All networked systems
	- Web applications
	- Databases
	- Network devices
	- Cloud services
	- Medical devices (with caution)
- Tools:
	- Authenticated scanning
	- Unauthenticated scanning
	- Web application scanners
	- Database scanners
	- Configuration compliance tools
Penetration Testing:
- Frequency:
	- Annual comprehensive test
	- After major infrastructure changes
	- Before critical system launches
- Types:
	- External penetration test
	- Internal penetration test
	- Web application test
	- Social engineering test
	- Physical security test
	- Wireless network test
- Approach:
	- Black box (no knowledge)
	- Gray box (limited knowledge)
	- White box (full knowledge)
- Deliverables:
	- Executive summary
	- Technical findings
	- Risk ratings
	- Remediation recommendations
	- Retest results
2. Collaboration Establishment
Establish Collaboration with Key Partners:
Supplier Collaboration:
- Regular security meetings
- Shared incident response procedures
- Joint exercises
- Security roadmap alignment
- Vulnerability disclosure process
- Escalation procedures
Managed Security Service Provider (MSSP):
- 24/7 monitoring
- Threat intelligence sharing
- Incident response support
- Regular reporting
- Quarterly business reviews
- Annual assessment
Other Hospitals and Healthcare Peers:
- Information Sharing and Analysis Center (H-ISAC)
- Regional healthcare networks
- Threat intelligence sharing
- Lessons learned exchange
- Joint exercises
- Peer support during incidents
Industry Organizations:
- Healthcare sector working groups
- Cybersecurity alliances
- Professional associations
- Best practice forums
3. National CSIRT and Authority Contact
Contact Your National CSIRT or Supervising Authority:
When to Contact:
- Significant security incidents
- Suspected state-sponsored attacks
- Widespread threats
- Critical vulnerability discoveries
- Ransomware attacks
- Data breaches affecting patients
- Regulatory reporting requirements
What to Report:
- Incident description
- Affected systems and data
- Number of affected individuals
- Actions taken
- Assistance needed
- Timeline of events
Follow Their Instructions:
- Guidance on containment
- Evidence preservation
- Notification requirements
- Media handling
- Coordination with other victims
Regulatory Notification Timelines:
