6.3 Disaster Recovery

Objective: Ensure business continuity through physical disaster preparedness
1. Equipment Safety
Unplug Equipment Safely if Issues Arise:
Emergency Situations:
- Smoke:
	- Activate fire alarm
	- Evacuate immediately
	- Follow fire procedures
	- Don't attempt to save equipment
- Water:
	- Identify source
	- Shut off water if safe
	- Power down affected equipment
	- Move equipment if possible
	- Document damage for insurance
- Power Issues:
	- Voltage fluctuations
	- Power surges
	- Brownouts
	- Complete outages
	- Lightning strikes
Safe Shutdown Procedures:
- Document current state
- Save work if possible
- Graceful shutdown preferred
- Emergency power off as last resort
- Label disconnected equipment
- Document actions taken
2. Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS)
Use Critical Devices with Uninterruptible Power Source:
UPS Protected Systems:
- Critical medical devices
- Life support equipment
- Servers (EHR, PACS)
- Network core equipment
- Telecommunications
- Emergency lighting
- Security systems
- Building management
UPS Requirements:
- Sufficient runtime (15-30 minutes typical)
- Automatic voltage regulation
- Surge protection
- Battery health monitoring
- Alarms for power events
- Network management interface
- Graceful shutdown capability
3. Generator Testing
Test UPS/Generator Fail-Over:
Testing Schedule:
- Monthly UPS battery tests
- Quarterly full load tests
- Annual generator under load
- Fail-over testing twice yearly
- After significant electrical work
- After utility power issues
Test Procedures:
- Planned with operations
- Off-peak hours
- Gradual load application
- Monitor all systems
- Document runtime
- Test automatic transfer switch
- Test generator startup
- Verify fuel levels
- Check for alarms
Success Criteria:
- Generator starts within 10 seconds
- Clean power transfer
- All critical systems remain operational
- No data loss
- No equipment damage
- Runtime meets requirements
- Clean shutdown when restored
4. Data Center Recovery Plan
Include Floods, Fires, or Power Outages:
Data Center Risks:
- Flooding (external, internal, HVAC leaks)
- Fire (equipment, electrical, external)
- Power outages (extended)
- Cooling failures
- Physical security breaches
- Structural damage
- Utility failures
- Environmental hazards
Recovery Plan Components:
Preparedness:
- Risk assessment
- Mitigation measures
- Flood barriers
- Fire suppression systems
- Raised floors
- Water detection sensors
- Environmental monitoring
Response:
- Emergency procedures
- Evacuation plans
- Equipment shutdown procedures
- Damage containment
- Evidence preservation
- Insurance notification
Recovery:
- Damage assessment
- Prioritized restoration
- Alternative site activation
- Equipment replacement
- Data restoration
- System validation
- Return to production
Alternative Sites:
- Hot site (fully operational)
- Warm site (partially equipped)
- Cold site (space only)
- Cloud-based DR
- Reciprocal agreement with peer
- Mobile data center
Testing Requirements:
- Annual full DR test
- Quarterly partial tests
- Tabletop exercises
- Documentation updates
- Staff training
- Vendor coordination
Recovery Time Objectives:
- Critical systems: 4-8 hours
- Standard systems: 24-48 hours
- Non-critical systems: 72+ hours
---

7. Manage the ICT Supply Chain


7.1 Procure Securely

Objective: Integrate security throughout the procurement lifecycle
1. IT Department Involvement
Involve IT Department:
When to Involve IT:
- Requirement gathering phase
- Vendor selection
- Product evaluation
- Contract negotiation
- Implementation planning
- Ongoing management
IT Responsibilities:
- Technical requirements definition
- Architecture compatibility review
- Integration assessment
- Security requirements specification
- Infrastructure needs identification
- Support requirements
2. Early Security Integration
Include Security Requirements at Earliest Stage:
Requirements Gathering:
Security Requirements Checklist:
- Authentication mechanisms (MFA support)
- Authorization and access controls
- Encryption (at rest and in transit)
- Audit logging capabilities
- Patch management process
- Vulnerability disclosure policy
- Incident response procedures
- Data residency options
- Backup and recovery
- API security
- Compliance certifications
- Security testing results
- Third-party component disclosure
RFP Security Section:
Include comprehensive security questionnaire covering:
- Security governance
- Access management
- Network security
- Application security
- Data protection
- Physical security
- Incident management
- Business continuity
- Compliance
- Personnel security
3. Supplier Compliance Verification
Verify Supplier Compliance with Standards:
Required Certifications:
International Standards:
- ISO 27001 (Information Security Management)
- ISO 27017 (Cloud Security)
- ISO 27018 (Cloud Privacy)
- ISO 27701 (Privacy Management)
- SOC 2 Type II (Security, Availability, Confidentiality)
Healthcare-Specific:
- HITRUST CSF Certified
- HIPAA compliance attestation (US markets)
- IEC 62304 (Medical device software)
- IEC 62443 (Industrial control systems)
Regional Compliance:
- GDPR compliance
- NIS2 compliance
- Medical Device Regulation (MDR)
- In Vitro Diagnostic Regulation (IVDR)
- National healthcare regulations
Verification Process:
- Request certification documents
- Verify certification validity
- Review audit reports
- Check certification scope
- Confirm ongoing compliance
- Review exceptions and caveats
