9. Physical Security


9.1 Perimeter Security

Objective: Control and monitor physical access to facilities
1. Badge Management
Make Sure Staff and Contractors Always Wear Badges:
Badge Requirements:
- Visible display at all times
- Photo ID badge
- Color-coded by role or area
- Expiration dates visible
- RFID/smart card technology
- Visitor badges distinct from staff
Badge Types:
Badge Type
Color
Access Level
Duration
Employee
Blue
Full authorized
Permanent (annual renewal)
Contractor
Yellow
Limited
Contract duration (max 1 year)
Visitor
Red
Escorted only
Single day
Vendor
Green
Specific areas
Pre-authorized period
Emergency
Orange
All areas
Duration of emergency
Temporary
White
As specified
Max 1 week
Badge Procedures:
- Issue on first day
- Return on last day
- Report lost/stolen immediately
- Deactivate immediately upon report
- Reissue fees for lost badges
- No badge sharing or lending
- Challenge unbadged individuals
- Escort requirement for visitors
2. Intrusion Alarm Maintenance
Maintain Intrusion Alarms:
Alarm System Components:
- Door/window sensors
- Motion detectors
- Glass break detectors
- Panic buttons
- Environmental sensors (smoke, water)
- Tamper switches
- Central monitoring station
Maintenance Schedule:
- Monthly battery checks
- Quarterly sensor tests
- Annual full system test
- After any incident
- After facility modifications
- Professional inspection annually
Alarm Response:
- 24/7 monitoring center
- Response procedures
- Law enforcement notification
- Staff notification
- Investigation protocols
- False alarm management
3. Entry and Exit Logging
Log Every Entry and Exit:
Access Control System:
- Electronic badge readers
- Time-stamped entries
- Location tracking
- Failed access attempts logged
- Forced door alerts
- Door held open alerts
- Tailgating detection
Log Retention:
- Minimum 90 days for routine access
- 1-2 years for sensitive areas
- Indefinite for incidents
- Regular review of logs
- Automated anomaly detection
What to Monitor:
- After-hours access
- Weekend access
- Access to restricted areas
- Multiple location access (impossible travel)
- High-frequency access
- Failed access attempts
- Forced entry events
4. Challenge Protocol
Encourage Approaching Unauthorized Persons:
Challenge Procedures:
- Polite but firm approach
- "May I see your badge?"
- "Are you lost? Can I help you?"
- Never physically confront
- Maintain safe distance
- Report to security immediately
- Don't assume someone else will check
Training Staff:
- Empower all staff to challenge
- "See something, say something"
- Non-confrontational techniques
- When to call security
- Personal safety first
- No retaliation for false reports
Security Culture:
- Everyone responsible for security
- Regular reminders
- Recognize good security behavior
- Management sets example
- Visitors expect to be challenged

9.2 Secure Workspaces & Facilities

Objective: Protect physical assets and information through facility security
1. Camera Coverage
Audit Camera Coverage and Store 30 Days:
Camera Placement:
- All entrances and exits
- Parking areas
- Server rooms and data centers
- Medical supply storage
- Pharmacy
- Corridors and stairwells
- Cash handling areas
- High-value equipment storage
- Sensitive document areas
Camera Specifications:
- High resolution (1080p minimum)
- Night vision capable
- Wide coverage angles
- Tamper-resistant
- Network-connected (secure VLAN)
- Encrypted video streams
- Backup power (UPS)
Recording and Storage:
- Continuous recording
- 30 days retention minimum (90 days for sensitive areas)
- Secure storage (access controlled)
- Encrypted storage
- Redundant copies
- Off-site backup
- Chain of custody for evidence
Regular Audits:
- Quarterly camera functionality check
- Coverage gap identification
- Blind spot assessment
- New area integration
- Image quality review
- Storage capacity monitoring
2. Physical Device Security
Physically Secure Devices, Cables & USB Sticks:
Device Security Measures:
Workstations and Laptops:
- Cable locks (Kensington locks)
- Secure docking stations
- Locked offices/rooms when not in use
- Asset tags
- Inventory tracking
- Encrypted hard drives
Servers and Network Equipment:
- Locked server rooms
- Rack locks
- Cable locks for portable equipment
- Environmental monitoring
- Access logging
- Video surveillance
Mobile Devices:
- Encrypted storage
- Remote wipe capability
- Never left unattended
- Secure storage when not in use
- Tracking enabled
- Find my device activated
USB and Removable Media:
- Encrypted USB drives only
- Minimal use (prefer network)
- Logged and tracked
- Physically secured when not in use
- Dispose securely
- Disable USB ports where possible
3. Fire Suppression
Use Fire Suppression:
Data Center Fire Suppression:
- Clean Agent Systems: (FM-200, Novec 1230)
	- No water damage
	- Safe for occupied spaces
	- Fast discharge
	- Regular inspections
- Pre-Action Sprinklers:
	- Double verification before water release
	- Minimal accidental discharge risk
	- Water damage as last resort
Fire Detection:
- Smoke detectors (early warning)
- Heat detectors
- Aspirating smoke detection (very early warning)
- Manual pull stations
- Integration with building fire alarm
Fire Suppression Procedures:
- Automatic suppression activation
- Audible alarms (evacuation warning)
- Power shutdown (some systems)
- HVAC shutdown
- Emergency response notification
- Staff evacuation procedures
Regular Maintenance:
- Monthly inspections
- Annual professional servicing
- Agent level checks
- Nozzle inspection
- Control panel testing
- Documentation of all tests
4. HVAC Management
Check Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning:
HVAC Critical for IT:
- Temperature control (18-27°C / 64-80°F)
- Humidity control (40-60%)
- Air filtering (dust reduction)
- Positive pressure
- Redundant systems
- Emergency cooling
Monitoring:
- 24/7 temperature monitoring
- Humidity monitoring
- Airflow monitoring
- Automated alerts
- Historical trending
- Integration with building management
Maintenance Schedule:
- Monthly filter changes
- Quarterly professional maintenance
- Annual comprehensive inspection
- Refrigerant level checks
- Ductwork inspection
- Condenser coil cleaning
HVAC Security:
- Secure mechanical rooms
- Access control
- Monitoring for tampering
- Separate HVAC network (no IT network)
- Vendor escort requirements
5. Emergency Preparedness
Know Where Emergency Exits and Fire Alarms Are:
Emergency Exit Requirements:
- Clearly marked exits
- Illuminated exit signs
- Unobstructed exit paths
- Regular drills (quarterly minimum)
- Assembly points designated
- Evacuation routes posted
- Emergency lighting
Fire Alarm Locations:
- Visible and accessible
- Regular testing (monthly)
- Staff training on use
- No obstruction
- Inspection tags current
Emergency Procedures:
- Fire
- Flood
- Power outage
- Hazardous materials
- Active shooter
- Bomb threat
- Natural disaster
- Cyber incident
Staff Training:
- Annual emergency training
- Role-specific responsibilities
- Evacuation procedures
- Assembly point locations
- Headcount procedures
- Special needs assistance
- Emergency contacts
- Return-to-work procedures
Emergency Equipment:
- Fire extinguishers (accessible, inspected monthly)
- AED (Automated External Defibrillators)
- First aid kits
- Emergency flashlights
- Two-way radios
- Emergency power
- Emergency phone system
---

10. Implementation Checklist


Phase 1: Immediate Actions (0-30 days)

Critical Quick Wins:
- [ ] Enable MFA on all external-facing systems
- [ ] Change all default passwords
- [ ] Enable automatic updates where safe
- [ ] Implement clean desk/clear screen policy
- [ ] Establish incident reporting hotline
- [ ] Create emergency contact list
- [ ] Enable email spam/phishing filtering
- [ ] Verify backups exist and are offline
- [ ] Conduct asset inventory
- [ ] Deploy antivirus/antimalware on all devices
Estimated Effort: 20-40 hours
Cost Impact: Low to Medium
Risk Reduction: High

Phase 2: Short-Term (1-3 months)

Foundation Building:
- [ ] Complete vulnerability scan of all systems
- [ ] Implement network segmentation plan
- [ ] Deploy SIEM or log management solution
- [ ] Create incident response plan
- [ ] Conduct phishing simulation baseline
- [ ] Implement application whitelisting
- [ ] Deploy mobile device management (MDM)
- [ ] Establish security training program
- [ ] Implement secure Wi-Fi (WPA3)
- [ ] Create and test backup restoration
- [ ] Deploy next-generation firewalls
- [ ] Implement privileged access management
- [ ] Establish supplier security requirements
- [ ] Conduct tabletop exercise
Estimated Effort: 200-400 hours
Cost Impact: Medium to High
Risk Reduction: Very High

Phase 3: Medium-Term (3-6 months)

Capability Enhancement:
- [ ] Deploy Web Application Firewall (WAF)
- [ ] Implement DDoS protection
- [ ] Deploy endpoint detection and response (EDR)
- [ ] Implement data classification system
- [ ] Deploy data loss prevention (DLP)
- [ ] Conduct penetration testing
- [ ] Implement user behavior analytics (UBA)
- [ ] Establish security metrics dashboard
- [ ] Create disaster recovery plan
- [ ] Test disaster recovery procedures
- [ ] Implement certificate-based authentication
- [ ] Deploy jump hosts for administration
- [ ] Establish H-ISAC membership
- [ ] Complete supplier security assessments
Estimated Effort: 400-800 hours
Cost Impact: High
Risk Reduction: Very High

Phase 4: Long-Term (6-12 months)

Maturity and Optimization:
- [ ] Achieve ISO 27001 certification
- [ ] Implement zero-trust architecture
- [ ] Deploy micro-segmentation
- [ ] Implement security automation and orchestration (SOAR)
- [ ] Establish red team program
- [ ] Implement advanced threat hunting
- [ ] Deploy deception technologies
- [ ] Achieve HITRUST certification
- [ ] Complete NIS2 compliance
- [ ] Implement continuous controls monitoring
- [ ] Establish bug bounty program
- [ ] Deploy AI/ML for threat detection
- [ ] Complete full DR site deployment
Estimated Effort: 800-1600 hours
Cost Impact: Very High
Risk Reduction: Comprehensive

Ongoing Activities (Continuous)

Maintain and Improve:
- [ ] Monthly phishing simulations
- [ ] Quarterly vulnerability scans
- [ ] Quarterly tabletop exercises
- [ ] Quarterly security awareness training
- [ ] Monthly security newsletter
- [ ] Weekly threat intelligence review
- [ ] Daily log review and monitoring
- [ ] Monthly patch deployment
- [ ] Quarterly access reviews
- [ ] Quarterly supplier reviews
- [ ] Annual penetration testing
- [ ] Annual disaster recovery test
- [ ] Annual security strategy review
- [ ] Continuous threat monitoring (24/7)
