11. Quick Reference Guide


Common Cyber Threats in Healthcare

Threat
Description
Impact
Primary Defense
Ransomware
Encrypts data, demands payment
Service disruption, data loss
Offline backups, patching, email filtering
Phishing
Fraudulent emails to steal credentials
Credential theft, malware delivery
Email filtering, MFA, user training
Insider Threat
Malicious or negligent staff
Data theft, sabotage
Access controls, monitoring, HR screening
Medical Device Exploit
Vulnerabilities in medical equipment
Patient safety, data breach
Network segmentation, patching, monitoring
DDoS
Overwhelm services with traffic
Service unavailability
DDoS mitigation service, capacity planning
Data Breach
Unauthorized data access/theft
Regulatory fines, reputation damage
Encryption, access controls, DLP

Emergency Response Numbers

During a Cyber Incident:
1. Call IT Help Desk: [Your number here]
2. Do not: Pay ransom, delete evidence, communicate with attacker
3. Do: Disconnect from network (if instructed), preserve evidence, document actions
4. Report to: National CSIRT, supervisory authority (within required timeframes)

Password Best Practices

Strong Password Formula:
- Minimum 12 characters
- Mix of uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols
- No dictionary words
- No personal information
- Unique for each account
- Use password manager
Example: Hlth$Care2025!Tx

Recognizing Phishing

Red Flags:
- Urgent language ("act now!")
- Requests for passwords or credentials
- Suspicious sender address
- Generic greetings ("Dear user")
- Spelling and grammar errors
- Unexpected attachments
- Suspicious links (hover to check)
- Too good to be true offers
When in Doubt: Don't click, report to IT

Data Classification Quick Guide

Classification
Examples
Email
Storage
Sharing
Highly Sensitive
Mental health, HIV status
Encrypt
Encrypt, restricted access
Minimal, audited
Sensitive
Diagnosis, prescriptions
Encrypt
Encrypt, controlled access
Need-to-know, audited
Confidential
Patient demographics
Secure protocol
Standard encryption
Internal only, logged
Public
Health education
Standard
Standard
Unrestricted

Clean Desk Checklist

Before Leaving Your Desk:
- [ ] Lock computer (Windows + L)
- [ ] Put away patient files
- [ ] Secure portable devices
- [ ] Lock drawers/cabinets
- [ ] Retrieve prints from printer
- [ ] Log out of applications
- [ ] Store USBs securely
- [ ] Clear whiteboard if patient data

